The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, January 07, 2004 				 Apex court backs CBI probe into Tata Fin
																								New Delhi, Jan. 6: The Supreme Court today upheld the Mumbai High Court order referring the Tata Finance case to the Central Bureau of Investigation (CBI) for a thorough probe into the financial irregularities.																								TFLs ousted managing director Dilip Pendse is an accused in the case. It has been alleged that he was involved in the misappropriation of funds.																								A division bench of Chief Justice V. N. Khare and Justice H. S. Kapadia, which upheld the high court order, however, expunged certain remarks of the high court against former Maharashtra deputy chief minister Chhagan Bhujbal.																								The Maharashtra government challenged the high court order transferring the investigation to CBI from the state CID. In a separate application, Bhujbal wanted the apex court to expunge certain observations made by the high court against him it its order.																								It had been alleged that Bhujbal was interfering with the investigations by the local police.																								In its FIR against Pendse and others filed in August 2001, Tata Finance had alleged that its former MD had misappropriated over Rs 400 crore from the companys funds between December 1999 and May 2000. 
